===Etymology===
From {{der|zh|sit-pro|*klaʔ||to fall}} (STEDT under PTB *(k/g)la-k/y/t, {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}):
:within Sinitic, cognate to {{och-l|露}} "dew", {{och-l|下|down, below, to descend, to fall down}} <!--Schuessler considered 下 to be one of 露's allofams besides 露 (from ST) & 蘀 (from AA); should we include this information?-->, {{och-l|陊}} "to collapse" and {{och-l|阤}} "hillside, slope";
:outside of Sinitic, cognate to {{cog|lus|tla|tla ~ tlâk|t=to fall}} and {{m|lus|thla|thla ~ thlâk|t=to drop}}, {{cog|my|ကျ||to fall}} and {{m|my|ချ||to drop}}.

Schuessler attributes OC *''r-'', instead of expected **''l-'', to possible Austroasiatic influence: compare {{cog|km|tr=gra'ka|t=be low, debased}} < {{m|km|tr=-ra'ka|t=to fall, below, cover from above}}. However, {{zh-ref|Matisoff (2003)}} identifies several ST etyma which display TB *''(C‑)l-'' vs. OC *''(C‑)r‑'' correspondence (e.g. {{m|sit-pro|*l(j)a(k/ŋ)||good, beautiful}} → {{och-l|良}}, {{m|sit-pro|*g/m-liŋ||neck}} → {{och-l|領}}, etc.) and TB *''(C‑)r-'' vs. OC *''(C‑)l‑'' (e.g. {{m|sit-pro|*g-rjum||salt}} → {{och-l|鹽|tr=*ɡ·lam}}); so irregularities in correspondence do not necessarily indicate foreign influences.

Contemporary southern usage possibly reinforced by a Kra-Dai term. The term has been associated with {{cog|za|loengx||to fall}}.

{{w|Zhengzhang Shangfang|Zhengzhang}} suggested that Pronunciation 2 was a result of loss of final consonant of the retained Old Chinese Pronunciation 1.

